Title : Samson Idiata
Text : '''Samson Idiata''' (born 23 January 1988 in [[Ewu]]<ref>[http://g2014results.thecgf.com/athlete/boxing/1021839/samson_idiata.html 2014 CWG profile]</ref>) is a [[Nigeria]]n [[high jump]]er and [[long jump]]er.<ref name=bio>{{iaaf name|198848}}</ref>

He took the bronze medal at the [[Athletics at the 2003 All-Africa Games – Men's high jump|2003 All-Africa Games]], and later finished fifth at the [[2006 African Championships in Athletics – Men's high jump|2006 African Championships]] and tenth at the [[Athletics at the 2007 All-Africa Games – Men's high jump|2007 All-Africa Games]]. He later switched to long jump. In this event he has finished eighth at the [[2010 African Championships in Athletics – Men's long jump|2010 African Championships]].

His personal best was 2.15 metres, first achieved in October 2003 in [[Hyderabad]] and later equalled once. In long jump his personal best is 8.00 metres, achieved in May 2013 in [[Castelló de la Plana|Castellón]].<ref name=bio/>

He was the gold medallist in the long jump at the [[2015 African Games]], but was stripped of this title after failing a drug test for [[clenbuterol]].<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/sport/athletics/doping-ban-shock-for-nigeria-1975054 Doping ban shock for Nigeria]. IOL (2016-01-24). Retrieved on 2016-01-24.</ref> He was banned for four years, until 15 September 2019.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/download/download?filename=c198d111-adda-475a-b8e5-0a5aedead6ea.pdf&urlslug=List%20of%20athletes%20currently%20serving%20a%20period%20of%20ineligibility%20as%20a%20result%20of%20an%20anti-doping%20rule%20violation%20under%20IAAF%20rules IAAF list of sanctioned athletes]</ref>

